            <p>N. Y. 4th Nov 1888<lb/></p>
            <p>My dear Sir<lb/></p>
            <p>I am in receipt of your favor<lb/> &#38; hasten to express my regret at hearing of<lb/> Mr Mandel&#39;s trouble.  I warned him be<lb/>&#45;fore he left for Philadelphia against vio<lb/>&#45;lating the laws of the state which I knew<lb/> were very stringent.  I told him of a man<lb/> named Blanckensee who traded in specta<lb/>&#45;cles&#44; having been arrested &#38; deprived of his<lb/> entire stock.  <hi rend="underline">He</hi> however considered him<lb/>&#45;self quite safe as the perfumes he would<lb/> sell were compounded by himself.<lb/></p>
            <p>You do not avow it&#44; but I readily conclude<lb/> that M&#45;&#45;owes his liberation to your kind<lb/> offices &#38; I accordingly thank you for<lb/> your intervention on his behalf.<lb/></p>
            <p>I enclose&#44; as requested a Cheque for &#36;20.<lb/>  I have made it payable to you as M&#45;&#45;<lb/>is unable to give his <sic>endorsation</sic>.<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>Will you kindly let him understand that the<lb/> balance now in my hands for him is &#36;20.16<lb/> against which is chargeable whatever amt<lb/> Messrs Levi Bros may claim for the bottles<lb/> which I imported from them.<lb/></p>
            <p>Thanking you again for your<lb/> kindness to the old man &#38; most personal<lb/> greetings to all<lb/>
                I am Yours Vy Faithfully<lb/> A P. Mendes<lb/></p>
            <p>Rev. Dr Morais.<lb/></p>
            </body>
    </text>
